<div id="review_3639860163" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3639860163" />
    <a title="William A." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/100288965-william-a"><img alt="William A." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578521635p2/100288965.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3639860163?book_show_action=true">Nov 11, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="William A." class="user" itemprop="url" name="William A." href="/user/show/100288965-william-a">William A.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover " href="/book/show/19035020-mary-chestnut-s-civil-war">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3639860163" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17794704424765451847">Raw source material? OK, maybe not so raw. This diary was edited extensively by Mary Chestnut after the late unpleasantness among the states, then the noted historian, C. Vann Woodward got to work on it. Still the diary is amazing! Mary Chestnut knew everyone and had a penchant for being at the right place at the important times. She was in Charleston when the war started, in Montgomery when the Confederacy was formed, and in Richmond during the Seven Days. She knew Jefferson Davis and met Rober</span>
  <span id="freeText17794704424765451847" style="display:none">Raw source material? OK, maybe not so raw. This diary was edited extensively by Mary Chestnut after the late unpleasantness among the states, then the noted historian, C. Vann Woodward got to work on it. Still the diary is amazing! Mary Chestnut knew everyone and had a penchant for being at the right place at the important times. She was in Charleston when the war started, in Montgomery when the Confederacy was formed, and in Richmond during the Seven Days. She knew Jefferson Davis and met Robert E. Lee on several occasions. Her depiction of life in the Southern states during the Civil War have been quoted extensively in many history books. <br /><br />Still, when reading this, it was hard not to notice how blythe the Southern gentry were about the cause of the war. They were so swept up in rooting for the home team, it might as well have been Clemson vs Notre Dame. It appears that slavery, euphemistically called "our peculiar institution" by Mary and her friends, was never discussed in polite society. She and they were in the forefront of the post-war propaganda blitz to deny that slavery was the cause of the death and destruction. Sympathetic historians like C. Vann Woodward aided and abetted the misinformation. It is good that we are now going back and exposing the ugly truth about "the glorious cause."</span>
  <a data-text-id="17794704424765451847" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

